The Limits of Panic
Copenhagen — We often hear that the world we know will end, usually described as an ecological collapse.
In fact, since the Roman Club published the seminal work "The Limits to Growth" more than forty years ago, its basic idea has been with us all along.
But time is not lenient.
"The Limits to Growth" of 1972 warned humanity that a catastrophic collapse was imminent.
However, since then, we have seen financial panic, but no real shortages or production collapse.
On the contrary, the resources created by human ingenuity are more than sufficient to meet human consumption.
Yet the basic idea of "The Limits to Growth" still holds: we continue a trend of being preoccupied with misleading solutions to minor issues, while ignoring major problems and wise solutions.
In the early 1970s, technological optimism faded, the Vietnam War became a disaster, societies fell into turmoil, and the economy stagnated.
Rachel Carson's 1962 book "Silent Spring" ignited panic about pollution and also sparked the modern environmental movement; Paul Ehrlich's 1968 title "The Population Bomb" said it all.
On the first Earth Day in 1970, people were pessimistic.
The intention of "The Limits to Growth" was to make people worried about resource depletion.
This is our fate, because too many people consume too much.
Even though our genius gives us some time, we will ultimately destroy the Earth and ourselves through pollution.
The only hope is to stop economic growth itself, reduce consumption, recycle, and force people to have fewer children, achieving social stability at a significantly poorer level than now.
This view still resonates today, despite being profoundly wrong.
For example, the authors of "The Limits to Growth" predicted that by 2013, the world would run out of aluminum, copper, gold, lead, mercury, molybdenum, natural gas, oil, silver, tin, tungsten, and zinc.
However, even though commodity prices have recently rebounded, overall they have fallen to one-third of their levels from 150 years ago.
Technological innovation has replaced mercury in batteries, dental materials, and thermometers, and by 2000, mercury consumption had decreased by 98%, and its price had fallen by 90%.
More broadly, since 1946, the supply of copper, aluminum, iron, and zinc has exceeded demand, thanks to the discovery of new reserves and more economical new refining technologies.
Similarly, oil and natural gas were originally expected to run out by 1990 and 1992 respectively; today, reserves of both are higher than in 1970, despite a significant increase in our consumption.
In the past six years, shale gas alone has doubled the potential natural gas reserves of the United States and halved the price.
As for economic collapse, the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change estimates that global per capita GDP will increase 14 times this century, with developing countries increasing 24 times.
"The Limits to Growth" was wrong because its authors overlooked the greatest resource: our own ingenuity.
Population growth has been slowing since the 1960s.
Food supply has not collapsed (1.5 billion hectares of arable land are being used, in addition to 2.7 billion hectares of reserves).
The rate of malnutrition has been halved, dropping from 35% of the world's population to 16%.
Pollution has not defeated us either.
The Club of Rome imagined a pastoral past where we had no particulate air pollution and were happy farmers, and in the future, heating chimneys would make it impossible for us to breathe. Reality is completely the opposite.
In 1900, the global population was only 1.5 billion, and nearly 3 million people — one in every 500 — died each year from air pollution, most of which was indoor air pollution.
Now, this ratio has dropped to one death in 2000 people.
Although pollution-related deaths are still higher than those from malaria, their mortality rate is declining rather than increasing.
Nevertheless, the ideas fostered by "The Limits to Growth" continue to influence the thinking of the public and elites.
Take recycling, for example; it is usually just a feel-good gesture that costs the environment a lot but yields little benefit.
For instance, paper usually comes from sustainable forests rather than tropical rainforests.
The processes and government subsidies related to paper recycling result in low-quality paper, protecting resources that are not under threat.
Similarly, policies concerned with overpopulation leading to self-destruction, such as China's family planning and India's forced sterilization.
Furthermore, although pesticides and other pollutants are believed to kill half of humanity, good pesticide regulation results in only 20 deaths per year in the United States, while the use of pesticides has created cheaper and more abundant food supplies.
In fact, relying solely on organic agriculture — a movement stimulated by pesticide panic — would bring an additional cost of $100 billion annually to the United States.
Agricultural efficiency would decrease by 16%, and to maintain current output, an additional 65 million hectares of farmland — half the area of modern California — would need to be cultivated.
Rising prices will lead to a decrease in fruit and vegetable consumption, causing serious negative health impacts (including an increase of tens of thousands of cancer deaths annually).
Getting obsessed with bleak scenarios prevents us from paying attention to the real global threats.
Poverty is one of the biggest killers, yet easily curable diseases still cause 15 million deaths annually — equivalent to a quarter of total deaths.
The solution lies in economic growth.
Once people escape poverty, most can afford the burden of preventing infectious diseases.
In the past thirty years, 680 million people in China have escaped poverty, leading the world in reducing the number of poor people by nearly one billion.
This has resulted in widespread improvements in health, life expectancy, and quality of life.
The forty-year history since the publication of "The Limits to Growth" shows that we need more growth, not less.
The expansion of trade is estimated to bring over $10 trillion in annual benefits by the end of this century, far surpassing the timid "safe" policies driven by fear-mongering.
But this requires abandoning anti-growth thinking and using our infinite potential to create a brighter future.
